   <title>Tutor</title>
   <question id="q1">
      <body>
         <p>If you have a room with 100 people, how unusual would it be to have no matches?</p>
<p>Feel free to run another simulation to help you to answer this
            question<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101105T172515-0400"?>.<?oxy_insert_end?></p>
      </body>
      <short_answer id="A"/><part>
         <response input="A" match="*" score="1"/>
         <explanation>
<p>Recall that with only 60 people the P(at least one match) was .994. Thus, it makes sense that if
               we have 100 people the probability of at least one match would be higher. This means
               the P(no matches) would be extremely low. In fact, it is about
               .000000303<?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101105T172611-0400" content="."?><?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101105T172628-0400"?>&#8212;<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101105T172558-0400" content=" Indeed"?><?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101105T172601-0400"?>very<?oxy_insert_end?>
               unlikely<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101105T172604-0400"?>
               indeed<?oxy_insert_end?>!</p>
         </explanation>
      </part>
   </question>
</assessment>
